Q1b: DirRec Method

# want to fit an auto.arima model then forecast for h = 1 
# add the prediction to train and repeat in a for loop for all 12 months

# create tmp df to preserve train
tmp_train = train

# create vector for results (preds, acf test, mean, normality)
preds = numeric(length(test))
means = numeric(length(test))
p_autocorr = numeric(length(test))
p_normality = numeric(length(test))

for(i in 1:length(test)){
  
  # fit the model and forecast to train
  mod = auto.arima(tmp_train)
  forecasts = forecast(mod, h = 1)$mean
  preds[i] = forecasts
  #tmp_train = c(tmp_train, forecasts)
  tmp_train = ts(c(tmp_train, forecasts), start = c(1975, 1),
                   frequency = 12)
  
  # get results 
  resids = residuals(mod)
  means[i] = mean(resids)
  lb_test = Box.test(resids, type = "Ljung-Box")
  p_autocorr[i] = lb_test$p.value
  sw_test = shapiro.test(resids)
  p_normality[i] = sw_test$p.value
}

Q1c: Checking Residuals

Checking Residuals for the Recursive Method:

# get residuals from model
resids1 = residuals(mod1)
# check mean 
cat("Mean of Residuals Recursive:", round(mean(resids1), 5))
## Mean of Residuals Recursive: -0.01226
# check ACF plot
acf(resids1, main = "ACF of Residuals Recursive Method")

# plot residuals vs. fitted values to examine the residuals
fits1 = fitted(mod1)
plot(y = resids1, x = fits1, 
     main = "Residuals vs. Fitted Values: Recursive Method",
     ylab = "Residuals", 
     xlab = "Fitted Values", col = "Light Blue")
abline(h = 0, col = "red", lty = 2)

qqnorm(resids1, main = "QQ Plot of Residuals: Recursive Method")
qqline(resids1, col = "red")

# LB test for auto correlation 
lb1 = Box.test(resids1, type = "Ljung-Box", lag = 12)
lb1
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  resids1
## X-squared = 5.0383, df = 12, p-value = 0.9567
sw1 = shapiro.test(resids1)
sw1
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  resids1
## W = 0.93789, p-value = 5.15e-07

Based on the ACF plot, we see that the lags are not significantly autocorrelated with each other. The LB autocorrelation test returns a p-value greater than 0.05, so we fail to reject the null hypothesis that the residuals are not autocorrelated. The residuals have a mean close to 0, are evenly distributed with no heteroskedascity in the residuals vs. fitted values plot, and they fall closely to the Normal on the QQ plot. However, the Shapiro-Wilkes test returns a p-value much less than 0.01, so we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the residuals are not normal. The residuals are not normal but they have no autocorrelation and approximately zero mean with constant variance, therefore they are random noise (but not Gaussian white noise specifically).

We observe that the means of the residuals are close to 0 for each of the 12 models. We also observe that the p-values for the LB test are all higher than 0.05, so for each model, we fail to reject the null hypothesis, indicating that the residuals are not autocorrelated. However, the normality test has p-values much less than 0.01 for each model, so we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the residuals for each model are not normal. The residuals are not normal but they have no autocorrelation and approximately zero mean with constant variance, therefore they are random noise (but not Gaussian white noise specifically).

The DirRec forecasting method takes a larger computation time since the model has to be fitted recursively 12 times whereas the recursive method only has to be fit once to predict the next 12 months. The additional models that need to be fit in the DirRec method increase the computation complexity of the method, causing it to take more time.

Part B:

cme = read.csv("cmeS.csv")
imm = read.csv("immS.csv")
iom = read.csv("iomS.csv")
# function for algorithm to clean time series 
clean_time_series <- function(df) {
  # put correct date format then sort by date
  df$DateOfSale <- as.Date(df$DateOfSale, format = "%m/%d/%Y")
  df <- df %>% arrange(DateOfSale)
  
  # create new df for cleaned data
  dates <- seq(as.Date("2001-01-01"), as.Date("2013-12-31"), by = "month")
  new_df <- data.frame(Date = dates, Price = NA)
  
  # loop through each month and fill in the prices
  # take median if multiple prices and do forward fill if missing
  for (i in 1:nrow(new_df)) {
    month_tmp <- df %>%
      filter(year(DateOfSale) == year(new_df$Date[i]) &
               month(DateOfSale) == month(new_df$Date[i]))
    
    if (nrow(month_tmp) > 0) {
      # median
      new_df$Price[i] <- median(month_tmp$price, na.rm = TRUE)
    } else {
      # forward fill
      if (i > 1) {
        new_df$Price[i] <- new_df$Price[i - 1]
      }
    }
  }
  # return cleaned data
  return(new_df)
}
# apply the function to each dataset
cme_new = clean_time_series(cme)
imm_new = clean_time_series(imm)
iom_new = clean_time_series(iom)
# plots for original vs cleaned data: CME 
cme_tmp = cme
cme_tmp$Date <- as.Date(cme$DateOfSale, format = "%m/%d/%Y")


plot(cme_tmp$Date, cme$price, type = "o", col = "blue", 
     xlab = "Date", ylab = "Price", main = "Time Series for CME",
     pch = 16, cex = 0.6, ylim = range(c(cme$price, cme_new$Price)))

points(cme_new$Date, cme_new$Price, col = "red", pch = 16, cex = 0.6)

     xlab = "Date", ylab = "Price", main = "Time Series for IOM",
     pch = 16, cex = 0.6, ylim = range(c(iom$price, iom_new$Price)))

points(iom_new$Date, iom_new$Price, col = "red", pch = 16, cex = 0.6)

legend("topright", legend = c("Original Data", "Cleaned Data"), 
       col = c("blue", "red"), pch = 16, cex = 0.8)

This algorithm works by first converting the date column into a standard format then sorting the data by date to ensure consistency for filling in the prices in correct order. Next, we create a new data frame that will contain the cleaned data using the range of dates in the original data. Finally, we loop through all of the months and year pairs in the original data for filling in the prices. In each iteration of the loop, we get the current year-month pair by indexing into the new data frame which contains no duplicates or missing months, then we filter for the rows in the original data frame for the given year-month pair. If there are no rows, we use forward fill and replace the missing value using the previous month’s price. Otherwise, we take the median price if there are one or more entries. Doing this for all year-month pairs allows us to get one price per month and clean the data of missing or multiple entries for any given month.

I used this method because I thought that it would be easiest to loop through each month sequentially to get the prices in correct time order, especially since we can sort by the date. Due to going forward in time, I decided to use forward fill as the imputation method rather than backwards or taking the mean or median of all of the prices. Additionally, since prices can vary so much, I decided to take the median if there is more than one price rather than the mean as median is less resistant to outliers and skewing compared to mean. At first I tried to run this algorithm using the Year and Month columns given in the original data frame, but this failed for the IOM dataset since it had some missing values in the Year and Month columns and they were stored as strings rather than ints like the other two datasets. After a lot of trial and error and debugging, I landed on using the DateofSale column to sort the data then manually creating a date range for the new dataframe.
